Elizabeth Weiser examines what compels communities, organizations, and nations to create museum spaces, and how museums operate as sites of both civic engagement and rhetorical persuasion. Moving beyond rhetorical explorations of museums as “memory sites,” she shows how they intentionally straddle the divides between style and content, intellect and affect, and unity and diversity, and why their portrayal of the past matters to civic life—and particularly studies of nationalism—in the present and future.Deeply researched and artfully argued, Museum Rhetoric sheds light on the public impact of cultural and aesthetic heritage and opens avenues of inquiry for scholars of museum studies and public history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aCultural property. 0aMuseumsxSocial aspects. 0aNational museumsxSocial aspects. 0aNationalism. 0aRhetoric. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh  acivic society.  acommunity.  acultural heritage.  aculture.  aengagement.  aheritage museum exhibits.  aidentity.  amemory.  amuseum.  anational identity.  anationalism.  anations.  aorganizations.  apersuasion.  apublic sphere.  arhetoric.  asociety.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311074523840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271080246?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271080246423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271080246/original  a978-3-11-074523-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK